message.content: {"steps":[{"output":"\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^{f(x)g(x)} \\ge \\left(\\frac{1}{8}\\right)^{g(x)}","explanation":"The given inequality is \\(\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^{f(x)g(x)} \\ge \\left(\\frac{1}{8}\\right)^{g(x)}\\)."},{"output":"\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^{f(x)g(x)} = \\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^{3g(x)}","explanation":"Since \\(\\frac{1}{8} = \\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^3\\), we can rewrite the right side as \\(\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^{3g(x)}\\)."},{"output":"f(x)g(x) \\le 3g(x)","explanation":"Taking the logarithm base \\(\\frac{1}{2}\\) on both sides, we get \\(f(x)g(x) \\le 3g(x)\\)."},{"output":"f(x) \\le 3","explanation":"Dividing both sides by \\(g(x)\\) (assuming \\(g(x) \\neq 0\\)), we get \\(f(x) \\le 3\\)."},{"output":"x = 2, 3, 4","explanation":"From the graph, \\(f(x) \\le 3\\) for \\(x = 2, 3, 4\\)."},{"output":"2 + 3 + 4 = 9","explanation":"The sum of all natural numbers \\(x\\) that satisfy the inequality is \\(2 + 3 + 4 = 9\\)."}],"final_answer":"\\MC: boxed{2}"}
